            <!--Simple Prose. Delete this <div/> if not used.-->
            <div type="poem">
                <head type="title">[Evening At <placeName corresp="#CHAMOUNI">Chamouni</placeName>]
                Â   <name><persName corresp="#JR">by John Ruskin</persName></name></head> 
                
                <l>Not such the night whose stormy might </l>
                <l>Heroic <persName corresp="#JBM">Balmat</persName> braved,<hi rend="superscript">1</hi> </l>
                <l>When, darkening on the Go&#x00FB;t&#x00E9;&#x02BC;s height, </l>
                <l>The tempest howled and raved. </l>
                <l>Upon the mighty hill, forlorn, </l>
                <l>He stood alone amid the storm; </l>
                <pb/>
                <l>Watching the last day gleams decay, </l>
                <l>Supposing its returning ray </l>
                <l>Should see him lying were asleep, </l>
                <l>With Alpine snow for winding sheet. </l>
                <l>Methinks I see him, as he stood </l>
                <l>Upon the ridge of snow; </l>
                <l>The battering burst of winds above,&#x2014;</l>
                <l>The cloudy precipice below,&#x2014;</l>
                <l>Watching the dawn. With proud delight </l>
                <l>He saw that long, tempestuous night </l>
                <l>Drive to the westward, and unfold </l>
                <l>The ocean snow&#x2010;fields, upward rolled, </l>
                <l>Bright with the morning&#x02BC;s glance of gold. </l>
                <l>It past away,&#x2014;the tossing flood </l>
                <l>Of changing vapour, headlong riding; </l>
                <l>And lo! the untrodden summit stood </l>
                <l>Accessibly beside him. </l>
                
                <p><hi rend="superscript">1</hi> [&#x201C;It is hardly necessary to remind the reader that this refers to the first ascent of 
                    <geogName corresp="#MONTBLANC">Mont Blanc</geogName> in <date when="1786">1786</date> by <persName corresp="#JBM">Jacques Balmat</persName>.&#x201D;&#x2014;<emph>Editor&#x02BC;s Note,</emph> 1891. The &#x201C;Go&#x00FB;t&#x00E9;&#x02BC;s height&#x201D; 
                    is the D&#x00F4;me, or the Aiguille, du Go&#x00FB;ter. For an account of <persName corresp="#JBM">Balmat</persName>&#x02BC;s ascent, see 
                    ch. iv. in <emph>The Annals of Mont Blanc</emph>, by C. E. Matthews (1896).]</p>
